            <h2>Service Pathways</h2>
            <div class="row">
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <h3 class="card-title">Community Action Project (CAP)</h3>
                            <p class="card-text">Community Action Project (CAP) is the culmination of a journey of service and community engagement. The actual project can be large or small and is something students develop and execute over sophomore and junior year. The project should spring from service experiences in grades 9-10 and should reflect an area of personal interest for the student. All projects should address a need that exists within our local, regional, national, or international community. Service Projects may not focus solely on fundraising or a one-day event. The CAP path allows students to design and implement a community-focused project. This involves:</p>
                            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
                                <li class="list-group-item">Identifying a community need</li>
                                <li class="list-group-item">Conducting research</li>
                                <li class="list-group-item">Planning and executing a project</li>
                                <li class="list-group-item">Presenting findings and experiences</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="col-md-6">
                    <div class="card">
                        <div class="card-body">
                            <h3 class="card-title">Community Through Service (CTS)</h3>
                            <p class="card-text">A Commitment to Service (CTS) is a long-term commitment a student makes to ONE organization. Most students will do their CTS after trying out various experiences in 9th and 10th grade; however, students can complete their CTS in 9th or 10th grade. All students present their CTS and/or CAP during junior year. The CTS path encourages students to engage deeply with a single organization. This involves:</p>
                            <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
                                <li class="list-group-item">Completing a minimum of 30 hours of service</li>
                                <li class="list-group-item">Organizations must be approved by Ms. St John</li>
                                <li class="list-group-item">Hours must be in person (not at home or at school)</li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
